A RESOLUTION
1 Creating the Joint Study Committee on Height Restrictions Surrounding Georgia Airports;
2 and for other purposes.
3 WHEREAS, Georgia is one of only three states that does not regulate the height of structures
4 surrounding its airports, leaving a significant gap in aviation safety and infrastructure; and
5 WHEREAS, tall structures at the end of a runway or within critical approach and departure
6 zones compromise aircraft operations and public safety, forcing airports to either relocate,
7 shorten, or otherwise modify runways, which are decisions that result in substantial financial
8 cost and, in many cases, could lead to the closure of smaller, rural airports; and
9 WHEREAS, the state has a vested interest in balancing the rights of private landowners with
10 the necessity of maintaining safe and operational airports, ensuring that aviation
11 infrastructure can continue to support economic growth, public safety, and connectivity
12 across Georgia; and
13 WHEREAS, a comprehensive and strategic policy approach is needed to assess and
14 implement reasonable height restrictions that protect aviation operations while also
15 respecting the rights of property owners and fostering economic development; and
