16 WHEREAS, study is needed to evaluate and recommend policies and possible legislative
17 actions that address the challenges posed by unregulated development near airports,
18 including:
19 (1) A comprehensive analysis of height restrictions in states with established policies in
20 order to identify best practices for adoption in Georgia;
21 (2) An assessment of the economic and operational impact of unregulated development
22 near airports, including the potential financial burden on airports forced to modify
23 infrastructure;
24 (3) Consideration of the legal implications of implementing height restriction regulations,
25 ensuring that any policy recommendations respect property rights while prioritizing
26 aviation safety;
27 (4) Engagement with key stakeholders, including airport operators, aviation industry
28 experts, economic development officials, and private property owners to gain a broad
29 perspective on this issue; and
30 (5) Development of legislative proposals or regulatory recommendations that strike a
31 balance between protecting Georgia's aviation infrastructure and preserving the interests
32 of private landowners.
33 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF
34 GEORGIA:
35 (1) Creation of joint study committee. There is created the Joint Study Committee on
36 Height Restrictions Surrounding Georgia Airports.
37 (2) Members and officers. The committee shall be composed of the following
38 members:
39 (A) The President of the Senate shall appoint four members of the Senate as members
40 of the committee, one of which shall be the chairperson of the Senate Transportation
